+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01AMCXNok78EEMBuHY1t1F6u","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Excellent progress! All tests pass except one - the concurrent OT test. The issue is that the OT transform is not producing the expected result. Let me analyze what's happening:\n\n- Document: \"abcd\" (version 1)\n- c1 sends: insert \"X\" at position 2 → \"abXcd\" (version 2)\n- c2 sends: insert \"Y\" at position 4, based on version 1\n\nWhen c2's op (insert Y at pos 4) gets transformed against c1's op (insert X at pos 2):\n- Since 4 > 2, Y's position shifts right by X's text length (1), so Y goes to position 5\n- After \"abXcd\", insert Y at position 5 → \"abXcdY\" ✓\n\nBut the test shows \"abXcYd\", meaning Y ended up at position 4 (which is between c and d in \"abXcd\"). This means the OT transform isn't being applied. Let me check - c2's operation has `version: sync2.version` which is 1. The server's version is now 2 after c1's op. So the server should find one concurrent op in the history and transform against it.\n\nLet me check the `operationHistory` slicing. The session starts with `operationHistory: []` and `version: 1` (from the database's latest version which is 1 due to the initial version created by `createDocument`). When the initial version is created in `createDocument`, it creates a version record with `{ type: 'init', content }`. In `getOrCreateSession`, we load versions and look for `parsed.op` — but the init version has `{ type: 'init', content }`, not `{ op: ... }`. So `session.operationHistory` stays empty.\n\nWhen c1's insert (version 1) arrives:\n- `baseVersion = 1`, `session.version = 1`\n- `concurrentOps = session.operationHistory.slice(1)` → `[]` (empty, correct since no ops since version 1)\n- Transform is a no-op, so the insert at position 2 is applied directly\n- `session.operationHistory.push(insert X at 2)` → history = [insertX]\n- `session.version++` → version = 2\n\nWhen